[8] USA (California)
Date: Thu 13 Mar 2014
Source: Fox 5 San Diego [edited]
http://fox5sandiego.com/2014/03/12/4th-measles-case-reported-in-san-diego/


A small outbreak of measles has grown, with a man potentially exposing others at 4 locations, the San Diego County Health and Human Services Agency announced Wednesday [12 Mar 2014]. The unidentified man is the 3rd person to catch measles from someone who contracted the illness while visiting the Philippines, according to the HHSA [Health and Human Services Agency].

The agency said the new victim might have exposed others on
- 3-7 Mar 2014 and 10 Mar 2014 at the Veterans' Affairs Clinic on Third Avenue in Chula Vista;
- 3 Mar and 9 Mar 2014, between 6:30 pm and 10:30 pm at the 24 Hour Fitness at 870 Amena Court in Chula Vista;
- 5 Mar 2014 between 6:30 pm and 9:30 pm and 9 Mar 2014, between 5 pm and 8 pm at Mater Dei Catholic Church at 1571 Magdalena Ave. in Chula Vista;
- 9 Mar 2014 from 3:30 pm to 5:30 pm at the Navy Exchange main store at Navy Base San Diego.

"Anyone who was at any of the specific locations should watch for symptoms and contact their health care provider by phone if they show any signs of the disease," said Dr. Wilma Wooten, the county's public health officer. "We ask people with symptoms to phone their doctor's office in advance, rather than visit an office directly, so that infection control measures may be implemented to prevent exposure to others."

The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends 2 doses of the vaccine: the 1st at 12 months of age, and the 2nd between ages 4 to 6 years.

Complications from measles are more common in children younger than 5 years old and adults 20 years and older, and include diarrhea, ear infection, and pneumonia. Death can occur from severe complications and the risk is higher among younger children and adults, according to the HHSA.

There is no treatment for measles, with bed rest, fluids, and fever control measures recommended for patients. People with complications may need treatment for their specific problem.

Information about measles and vaccinations is available by calling the HHSA Immunization Branch at (866) 358-2966 or visiting the website at http://www.sdiz.org. People without a health provider can contact the HHSA Epidemiology Branch at (619) 692-8499.

