[9] USA (California)
Date: Fri 14 Mar 2014
Source: Orange County Register [edited]
http://www.ocregister.com/articles/march-605751-measles-mission.html


Two more people in Orange County got measles in the past week, bringing the total number of cases in the county to 7 since December [2013].

The county's Health Care Agency reported Friday [14 Mar 2014] that the 2 most recent cases visited numerous public places around the county during the time they were infectious.

Following exposure, symptoms normally appear within 7 to 10 days. The rash sets in 2 to 4 days later, usually starting around the ears and hairline, then moving to the face, torso, and limbs. Measles is contagious between about 4 days before the rash appears until about 4 days afterward, so other people might have been exposed at the places where patients have visited.

Here's a list of the known sites the 2 latest cases went, with dates and times:
- 3 Mar 2014, 9:30 to 11 am and 7 Mar 2014 1:30 to 3 pm: St. Joseph Heritage Healthcare Medical Office, 4300 Rose Drive, Suite D, Yorba Linda;
- 4 Mar 2014, 1-3 pm: Panda Express, 27602 Antonio Pkwy., Suite G3, Ladera Ranch;
- 5 Mar 2014, 9:30 to 11:30 am: Friends Christian Elementary School, 5151 Lakeview Ave., Yorba Linda;
- 6 Mar 2014, 6:30 to 9 pm: Robinson Ranch School, 21400 Lindsay Drive, Trabuco Canyon;
- 8 Mar 2014, 11:30 am to 1 pm: Placentia-Linda Hospital Emergency Department, 1301 N. Rose Drive, Yorba Linda;
- 9 Mar 2014, 1 to 2:30 pm: Kids Doc, 27800 Medical Center Road, Mission Viejo;
- 9 Mar 2014, 9:50 am to 3:45 pm and 10 Mar 2014, 11:25 am to 12:30 pm: Mission Hospital, Mission Viejo, Emergency Department, 27700 Medical Center Road., Mission Viejo;
- 10 Mar 2014, 11:25 am to 11 Mar 2014, 4:30 pm: Mission Hospital, Mission Viejo, CHOC Pediatric Medical Surgical Department, 27700 Medical Center Road, Mission Viejo.

Measles is rare in the United States, but cases are up sharply this season, including around California. In a normal year, Orange County will have no more than one case.

"We expect to see additional measles cases in Orange County, increasing the likelihood that you and your family may be exposed to the disease," Dr Eric Handler, the county's Public Health Officer, said in a statement. "These new measles cases underscore the importance of making sure that you and your families are up to date with the MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) vaccination."

