[11] USA (New Jersey, national)
Date: Thu 13 Mar 2014
Source: Healthcare Examiner [edited]
http://www.examiner.com/article/more-measles-cases-across-the-u-s


Bayonne, New Jersey, is the latest American community to experience a measles scare. NJ.com is reporting today, 13 Mar 2014, that an elementary school teacher in the Bayonne school system is being tested for the highly contagious respiratory illness. He teaches at the Midtown Community Elementary School which has more than 1000 students in grades K-8.

New York City has another 3 measles cases in its current outbreak, WPIX reported. The station also reports that 2 of the 19 cases in the outbreak were exposed while in a doctor's waiting room. On [11 Mar 2014], WNBC 4 reported that measles cases had spread to Brooklyn from the original locales in upper Manhattan and the Bronx. The city's Health Department had announced the outbreak on [7 Mar 2014], when there were 16 cases.

On [11 Mar 2014], the Connecticut Department of Public Health announced 2 cases of measles in Fairfield County. One case is in a never-immunized adult and the other in a 7-month-old infant, too young to be immunized. WFSB reported on that same day that the cases are unrelated. The station quoted health officials as expecting further measles cases among the contacts of the 2 original patients.

Measles has also spread in San Diego [California] where a traveler to the Philippines returned with the illness last month [February 2014]. The San Diego Health and Human Services Agency reported [12 Mar 2014] that a 4th patient had been diagnosed with measles. The 3 locally acquired cases are all connected to exposure to the original case in the traveler. The latest patient is known to have visited many public locations between [3 and 9 Mar 2014]. Measles is contagious up to 4 days before any rash appears.

Through [1 Mar 2014], the Centers for Disease Control had received reports of 51 measles cases in the United States. The reporting of illnesses can lag as much as 2 weeks and the CDC always suggests that the reporting at the state and local level is the most current.

Measles is a preventable illness. The MMR vaccine, given in 2 doses before the age of 5, is effective in preventing the illness, according to the Centers for Disease Control. Concerns about the safety of the vaccine are unfounded and without any scientific basis.

